@Code
    PageData("Title") = "Design Style: Minimalist"
    PageData("art_sub_title") = ""
    Layout = "~/designthreads/_DTLayout.vbhtml"
    PageData("description") = "'Less Is More', the well-known mantra of minimalist interior designers, was coined by architect Ludwig Mies van der Rohe to describe the extreme impression of simplicity in regards to a home's design."
End Code

	
<div class="spacer"></div>
<p class="opening">@PageData("description")</p>
<div class="spacer"></div>

<p>Influenced strongly by the Japanese 'Feng Sui', minimalist interiors are the epitome of sophisticated simplicity. Focused on the quality, rather than the quantity, these spaces rely heavily on the integrity of each piece within them. The concept of utter simplicity may seem cold and lackluster, however minimalist designs are meant to be restful and soothing. Their purposeful lack of ornamentation and decor allow the space to speak for itself. </p>		
<p>One of the key factors in minimalist interiors is open space, but it can appear cold and unwelcoming if not properly contained. Alleviate the hollow feeling vast empty spaces can create by utilizing repetition. Uniform repetition adds substance without creating visual clutter. Following with the concept of repetition, minimalist interiors maintain a singular color throughout the home. This continuity of color blends each space seamlessly into the next, creating the visual openness that is so important in these designs. Choosing a neutral wall color, rather than white, helps bring warmth into the home. While white may be predominant, it can come across as stark if not accented appropriately. Implementing a bold accent color though requires restraint. They can easily overwhelm the serenity minimalist spaces should evoke. Small doses scattered throughout will add emphasis without being obtrusive. Similarly patterns of any kind must also be handled carefully. Their nature is to attract attention and in minimalist interiors the attention is given to the space rather than what is in it. Subtle, tone on tone patterns are best suited for these designs and should remain as neutral in color as the room allows. Substituting texture for pattern is another easy way to add visual interest. Coordinated textures used sparingly can give the design depth. From sleek surfaces to raw edges, textures bring a humanizing effect, making the space feel friendly and livable.</p>
<div class="spacer"></div>

